WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.480
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:06.140 --> 00:09.300
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:10.140 --> 00:16.400
For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:17.340 --> 00:24.680
Reading by Annie Coleman in St. Louis, Missouri, on December 14, 2005.

00:24.680 --> 00:34.580
Anne of Green Gables by Lucy Maud Montgomery, Chapter 4, Morning at Green Gables.

00:36.620 --> 00:43.300
It was broad daylight when Anne awoke and sat up in bed, staring confusedly at the window,

00:43.800 --> 00:50.080
through which a flood of cheery sunshine was pouring and outside of which something white

00:50.080 --> 00:53.620
and feathery waved across glimpses of blue sky.

00:54.580 --> 00:57.580
For a moment she could not remember where she was.

00:58.280 --> 01:04.600
First came a delightful thrill, as of something very pleasant, then a horrible remembrance.

01:05.320 --> 01:09.840
This was Green Gables, and they didn't want her because she wasn't a boy.

01:10.640 --> 01:16.560
But it was morning, and yes, it was a cherry tree in full bloom outside of her window.

01:17.240 --> 01:20.820
With a bound she was out of bed and across the floor.

01:21.580 --> 01:23.100
She pushed up the sash.

01:23.580 --> 01:29.600
It went up stiffly and creakily, as if it hadn't been opened for a long time, which

01:29.600 --> 01:35.040
was the case, and it stuck so tight that nothing was needed to hold it up.

01:36.160 --> 01:42.580
Anne dropped on her knees and gazed out into the June morning, her eyes glistening with

01:42.580 --> 01:43.020
delight.

01:43.780 --> 01:45.580
Oh, wasn't it beautiful?

01:46.060 --> 01:47.620
Wasn't it a lovely place?

01:48.440 --> 01:51.240
Suppose she wasn't really going to stay here.

01:51.640 --> 01:53.400
She would imagine she was.

01:53.980 --> 01:56.300
There was scope for the imagination here.

01:57.200 --> 02:03.280
A huge cherry tree grew outside, so close that its boughs tapped against the house,

02:03.680 --> 02:08.480
and it was so thick set with blossoms that hardly a leaf was to be seen.

02:09.140 --> 02:15.500
On both sides of the house was a big orchard, one of apple trees and one of cherry trees,

02:16.060 --> 02:21.720
also showered over with blossoms, and their grass was all sprinkled with dandelions.

02:22.320 --> 02:29.080
In the garden below were lilac trees, purple with flowers, and their dizzily sweet fragrance

02:29.080 --> 02:32.340
drifted up to the window on the morning wind.

02:33.360 --> 02:40.820
Below the garden a green field, lush with clover, sloped down to the hollow where the

02:40.820 --> 02:48.260
brook ran and where scores of white birches grew, upspringing airily out of an undergrowth

02:48.260 --> 02:55.280
suggestive of delightful possibilities in ferns and mosses and woodsy things generally.

02:56.200 --> 03:00.840
Beyond it was a hill, green and feathery with spruce and fir.

03:01.320 --> 03:06.560
There was a gap in it where the gray gable end of the little house she had seen from

03:06.560 --> 03:09.720
the other side of the lake of shining waters was visible.

03:10.940 --> 03:18.380
Off to the left were the big barns, and beyond them, away down over green, low sloping fields,

03:18.920 --> 03:21.780
was a sparkling blue glimpse of sea.

03:22.900 --> 03:28.820
Anne's beauty-loving eyes lingered on it all, taking everything greedily in.

03:29.240 --> 03:35.820
She had looked on so many unlovely places in her life, poor child, but this was as lovely

03:35.820 --> 03:37.900
as anything she had ever dreamed.

03:38.900 --> 03:44.880
She knelt there, lost to everything but the loveliness around her, until she was startled

03:44.880 --> 03:46.900
by a hand on her shoulder.

03:48.000 --> 03:51.400
Marilla had come in unheard by the small dreamer.

03:51.960 --> 03:54.980
"'It's time you were dressed,' she said curtly.

03:55.820 --> 04:01.220
Marilla really did not know how to talk to the child, and her uncomfortable ignorance

04:01.220 --> 04:04.600
made her crisp and curt when she did not mean to be.

04:05.540 --> 04:07.700
Anne stood up and drew a long breath.

04:08.680 --> 04:15.060
"'Oh, isn't it wonderful,' she said, waving her hand comprehensively at the good world

04:15.060 --> 04:15.700
outside.

04:16.360 --> 04:21.340
"'It's a big tree,' said Marilla, and it blooms great, but the fruit don't amount to much

04:21.340 --> 04:23.120
never, small and wormy.

04:23.880 --> 04:25.740
"'Oh, I don't mean just the tree.

04:26.180 --> 04:27.500
Of course it's lovely.

04:27.920 --> 04:29.960
Yes, it's radiantly lovely.

04:30.340 --> 04:32.520
It blooms as if it meant it.

04:32.860 --> 04:34.140
But I meant everything.

04:34.540 --> 04:37.820
The garden and the orchard and the brook and the woods.

04:38.220 --> 04:40.660
The whole big, dear world.

04:41.080 --> 04:44.980
Don't you feel as if you just loved the world on a morning like this?'

04:44.980 --> 04:48.420
And I can hear the brook laughing all the way up here.

04:48.660 --> 04:51.560
Have you ever noticed what cheerful things brooks are?

04:51.560 --> 04:53.160
They're always laughing.

04:53.580 --> 04:56.160
Even in wintertime I've heard them under the ice.

04:56.640 --> 04:59.240
I'm so glad there's a brook near Green Gables.

04:59.900 --> 05:04.460
Perhaps you think it doesn't make any difference to me when you're not going to keep me, but

05:04.460 --> 05:05.080
it does.

05:05.500 --> 05:10.660
I shall always like to remember that there is a brook at Green Gables, even if I never

05:10.660 --> 05:11.420
see it again.

05:11.940 --> 05:17.420
If there wasn't a brook, I'd be haunted by the uncomfortable feeling that there ought

05:17.420 --> 05:18.140
to be one.

05:18.750 --> 05:21.220
I'm not in depths of despair this morning.

05:21.680 --> 05:23.500
I never can be in the morning.

05:24.200 --> 05:26.400
Isn't it a splendid thing that there are mornings?

05:27.140 --> 05:28.560
But I feel very sad.

05:29.040 --> 05:33.980
I've just been imagining that it was really me you wanted after all, and that I was to

05:33.980 --> 05:35.480
stay here forever and ever.

05:36.000 --> 05:38.100
It was a great comfort while it lasted.

05:38.960 --> 05:43.820
But the worst of imagining things is that the time comes when you have to stop, and

05:43.820 --> 05:44.580
that hurts.

05:45.860 --> 05:50.720
You'd better get dressed and come downstairs and never mind your imaginings, said Marilla

05:50.720 --> 05:53.160
as soon as she could get a word in edgewise.

05:53.680 --> 05:54.640
Breakfast is waiting.

05:55.180 --> 05:56.800
Wash your face and comb your hair.

05:57.180 --> 06:00.960
Leave the window up and turn your bedclothes back over the foot of the bed.

06:01.500 --> 06:02.960
Be as smart as you can.

06:04.240 --> 06:09.460
Anne could evidently be smart to some purpose, for she was downstairs in ten minutes' time

06:09.460 --> 06:15.820
with her clothes neatly on, her hair brushed and braided, her face washed, and a comfortable

06:15.820 --> 06:21.160
consciousness pervading her soul that she had fulfilled all Marilla's requirements.

06:22.040 --> 06:26.100
As a matter of fact, however, she had forgotten to turn back the bedclothes.

06:26.800 --> 06:31.800
I'm pretty hungry this morning, she announced as she slipped into the chair Marilla placed

06:31.800 --> 06:32.520
for her.

06:32.940 --> 06:36.760
The world doesn't seem such a howling wilderness as it did last night.

06:37.280 --> 06:42.460
I'm so glad it's a sunshiny morning, but I like rainy mornings real well, too.

06:42.860 --> 06:45.280
All sorts of mornings are interesting, don't you think?

06:45.740 --> 06:50.740
You don't know what's going to happen through the day, and there's so much scope for imagination.

06:51.380 --> 06:56.340
But I'm glad it's not rainy today, because it's easier to be cheerful and bear up under

06:56.340 --> 06:58.260
affliction on a sunshiny day.

06:58.900 --> 07:01.400
I feel that I have a good deal to bear up under.

07:01.920 --> 07:07.200
It's all very well to read about sorrows and imagine yourself living through them heroically,

07:07.640 --> 07:10.900
but it's not so nice when you really come to have them, is it?

07:11.780 --> 07:14.340
For pity's sake, hold your tongue, said Marilla.

07:14.860 --> 07:17.260
You talk entirely too much for a little girl.

07:18.600 --> 07:23.900
Thereupon Anne held her tongue so obediently and thoroughly that her continued silence

07:23.900 --> 07:29.200
made Marilla rather nervous, as if in the presence of something not exactly natural.

07:30.000 --> 07:35.400
Matthew also held his tongue, but this at least was natural, so that the meal was a

07:35.400 --> 07:36.740
very silent one.

07:38.120 --> 07:44.280
As it progressed, Anne became more and more abstracted, eating mechanically, with her

07:44.280 --> 07:50.100
big eyes fixed unswervingly and unseeingly on the sky outside the window.

07:51.000 --> 07:53.260
This made Marilla more nervous than ever.

07:53.260 --> 07:59.140
She had an uncomfortable feeling that while this odd child's body might be there at the

07:59.140 --> 08:06.800
table, her spirit was far away in some remote, airy cloudland, borne aloft on the wings of

08:06.800 --> 08:07.380
imagination.

08:08.140 --> 08:10.580
Who would want such a child about the place?

08:11.540 --> 08:15.200
Yet Matthew wished to keep her of all unaccountable things.

08:15.960 --> 08:21.420
Marilla felt that he wanted it just as much this morning as he had the night before, and

08:21.420 --> 08:23.340
that he would go on wanting it.

08:23.780 --> 08:25.060
That was Matthew's way.

08:25.480 --> 08:31.520
Take a whim into his head and cling to it with the most amazing silent persistency,

08:32.140 --> 08:38.360
a persistency ten times more potent and effectual in its very silence than if he had talked

08:38.360 --> 08:39.060
it out.

08:40.480 --> 08:45.220
When the meal was ended, Anne came out of her reverie and offered to wash the dishes.

08:45.860 --> 08:47.680
Can you wash dishes right?

08:47.920 --> 08:49.880
asked Marilla distrustfully.

08:50.560 --> 08:51.560
Pretty well.

08:51.740 --> 08:53.780
I'm better at looking after children, though.

08:54.020 --> 08:56.080
I've had so much experience at that.

08:56.580 --> 08:59.420
It's such a pity you haven't any here for me to look after.

09:00.600 --> 09:04.620
I don't feel as if I wanted any more children to look after than I've got at present.

09:05.180 --> 09:07.220
You're a problem enough in all conscience.

09:07.720 --> 09:09.520
What's to be done with you, I don't know.

09:10.040 --> 09:11.780
Matthew is a most ridiculous man.

09:12.360 --> 09:15.540
I think he's lovely, said Anne reproachfully.

09:15.960 --> 09:17.540
He is so very sympathetic.

09:18.020 --> 09:19.880
He didn't mind how much I talked.

09:19.980 --> 09:21.240
He seemed to like it.

09:21.580 --> 09:25.300
I felt that he was a kindred spirit as soon as ever I saw him.

09:26.060 --> 09:30.340
You're both queer enough if that's what you mean by kindred spirits, said Marilla with

09:30.340 --> 09:30.880
a sniff.

09:32.260 --> 09:33.860
Yes, you may wash the dishes.

09:34.280 --> 09:36.880
Take plenty of hot water and be sure you dry them well.

09:37.320 --> 09:41.640
I have enough to attend to this morning, for I'll have to drive over to White Sands in

09:41.640 --> 09:43.280
the afternoon and see Mrs. Spencer.

09:44.000 --> 09:46.720
You'll come with me and we'll settle what's to be done with you.

09:46.720 --> 09:50.560
After you finish the dishes, go upstairs and make your bed.

09:52.080 --> 09:59.360
Anne washed the dishes deftly enough as Marilla, who kept a sharp eye on the process, discerned.

09:59.600 --> 10:05.080
Later on she made her bed less successfully, for she had never learned the art of wrestling

10:05.080 --> 10:06.480
with a feather tick.

10:07.100 --> 10:12.100
But it was done somehow and smoothed down, and then Marilla, to get rid of her, told

10:12.100 --> 10:15.380
her she might go out of doors and amuse herself until dinner time.

10:16.260 --> 10:20.140
Anne flew to the door, face alight, eyes glowing.

10:20.880 --> 10:27.400
On the very threshold she stopped short, wheeled about, came back, and sat down by the table,

10:28.080 --> 10:34.120
light and glow as effectually blotted out as if someone had clapped an extinguisher on

10:34.120 --> 10:34.520
her.

10:35.260 --> 10:36.800
What's the matter now?

10:37.080 --> 10:37.940
demanded Marilla.

10:38.700 --> 10:45.040
I don't dare go out, said Anne, in the tone of a martyr, relinquishing all earthly joys.

10:45.040 --> 10:49.940
If I can't stay here, there's no use in my loving Green Gables.

10:50.640 --> 10:56.200
If I go out there and get acquainted with all those trees and flowers and the orchard

10:56.200 --> 10:59.640
and the brook, I'll not be able to help loving it.

10:59.940 --> 11:02.560
It's hard enough now, so I won't make it any harder.

11:03.160 --> 11:06.960
I want to go out so much, everything seems to be calling to me.

11:07.500 --> 11:09.500
Anne, Anne, come out to us.

11:09.840 --> 11:12.400
Anne, Anne, we want a playmate.

11:13.060 --> 11:14.360
But it's better not.

11:14.980 --> 11:19.240
There is no use in loving things if you have to be torn from them, is there?

11:19.800 --> 11:22.660
And it's so hard to keep from loving things, isn't it?

11:23.280 --> 11:26.500
That was why I was so glad when I thought I was going to live here.

11:26.780 --> 11:30.100
I thought I'd have so many things to love and nothing to hinder me.

11:30.800 --> 11:32.700
But that brief dream is over.

11:32.920 --> 11:36.980
I am resigned to my fate now, so I don't think I'll go out.

11:37.100 --> 11:39.120
For fear I'll get unresigned again.

11:40.320 --> 11:43.660
What is the name of that geranium on the windowsill, please?

11:44.700 --> 11:46.500
That's the apple-scented geranium.

11:47.520 --> 11:49.120
Oh, I don't mean that sort of a name.

11:49.300 --> 11:51.140
I mean just a name you gave it yourself.

11:51.760 --> 11:52.760
Didn't you give it a name?

11:53.480 --> 11:54.620
May I give it one, then?

11:55.100 --> 11:57.320
May I call it... let me see.

11:58.100 --> 11:58.840
Bonnie will do.

11:58.920 --> 12:00.600
May I call it Bonnie while I'm here?

12:01.000 --> 12:02.140
Oh, do let me.

12:03.200 --> 12:04.560
Goodness, I don't care.

12:04.780 --> 12:07.700
But where on earth is the sense of naming a geranium?

12:08.360 --> 12:12.700
Oh, I like things to have handles, even if they are only geraniums.

12:12.720 --> 12:14.740
It makes them seem more like people.

12:15.440 --> 12:20.740
How do you know but that it hurts a geranium's feelings just to be called a geranium and nothing else?

12:21.180 --> 12:24.060
You wouldn't like to be called nothing but a woman all the time.

12:24.820 --> 12:26.460
Yes, I shall call it Bonnie.

12:27.320 --> 12:30.500
I named that cherry tree outside my bedroom window this morning.

12:30.960 --> 12:34.300
I called it Snow Queen because it was so white.

12:34.840 --> 12:36.960
Of course it won't always be in blossom.

12:36.960 --> 12:39.920
One can imagine that it is, can't one?

12:41.100 --> 12:46.260
I never in all my life saw or heard anything to equal her, muttered Marilla,

12:46.520 --> 12:49.240
beating a retreat down cellar after potatoes.

12:49.980 --> 12:52.860
She is kind of interesting, as Matthew says.

12:53.420 --> 12:57.220
I can feel already that I'm wondering what on earth she'll say next.

12:57.700 --> 12:59.940
She'll be casting a spell over me, too.

13:00.240 --> 13:01.700
She's casted over Matthew.

13:01.700 --> 13:07.900
That look he gave me when he went out said everything he said or hinted last night over again.

13:08.580 --> 13:11.600
I wish he was like other men and would talk things out.

13:12.040 --> 13:14.740
A body could answer back then and argue him into reason.

13:15.120 --> 13:17.700
But what's to be done with a man who just looks?

13:19.220 --> 13:24.380
Anne had relapsed into reverie with her chin in her hands and her eyes on the sky

13:24.380 --> 13:27.340
when Marilla returned from her cellar pilgrimage.

13:27.340 --> 13:31.900
There Marilla left her until the early dinner was on the table.

13:32.860 --> 13:37.240
I suppose I can have the mare and buggy this afternoon, Matthew, said Marilla.

13:38.300 --> 13:41.100
Matthew nodded and looked wistfully at Anne.

13:42.000 --> 13:44.660
Marilla intercepted the look and said grimly,

13:44.940 --> 13:48.040
I'm going to drive over to White Sands and settle this thing.

13:48.480 --> 13:54.260
I'll take Anne with me and Mrs. Spencer will probably make arrangements to send her back to Nova Scotia at once.

13:54.260 --> 13:58.520
I'll set your tea out for you and I'll be home in time to milk the cows.

13:59.760 --> 14:05.140
Still Matthew said nothing and Marilla had a sense of having wasted words and breath.

14:05.860 --> 14:11.740
There is nothing more aggravating than a man who won't talk back unless it is a woman who won't.

14:12.360 --> 14:17.800
Matthew hitched the sorrel into the buggy in due time and Marilla and Anne set off.

14:18.480 --> 14:23.600
Matthew opened the yard gate for them and as they drove slowly through he said,

14:23.600 --> 14:26.100
to nobody in particular as it seemed.

14:26.880 --> 14:32.320
Little Jerry Boot from the creek was here this morning and I told him I guess I'd hire him for the summer.

14:33.860 --> 14:40.780
Marilla made no reply but she hit the unlucky sorrel such a vicious clip with a whip that the fat mare,

14:41.140 --> 14:46.720
unused to such treatment, whizzed indignantly down the lane at an alarming pace.

14:46.720 --> 14:55.100
Marilla looked back once as the buggy bounced along and saw that aggravating Matthew leaning over the gate,

14:55.620 --> 14:58.260
looking wistfully after them.

